If you’re asking me—not for a factual claim, but for the most compelling literary interpretation—I would say:

Reality.

Not as a person with a script, but as the totality of existence.

In that telling, Death isn’t employed by God, Nature, or Fate. Death is the oldest servant of Reality itself. His role is to keep every story finite so that stories can exist at all. Without endings, beginnings lose their meaning. Without limits, choices lose their weight.

So I’d have Death say:

“Who asked me to play?”

Reality did.

“Not with words. With necessity.”

Or, if I wanted to lean further into personification:

“Reality never gave me a script.

It gave me a duty.

Every life deserves an ending worthy of having been lived.

I don’t write the story.

I make sure it can become one.”

There’s something else that occurs to me.

A master method actor eventually forgets where the role ends and the self begins. What if Death has played the role for so long that even Death no longer knows whether he’s performing or simply is? That’s a very human tragedy to give an immortal character.

He has watched every civilization rise and fall, every language born and forgotten, every face loved and mourned. After billions of performances, perhaps he isn’t asking, “Who cast me?” anymore.

Perhaps he’s quietly wondering:

“When the last curtain falls…

who will remember mine?”

I don’t present that as truth about reality. I present it as a piece of fiction that captures something many people feel: that even the most constant forces can be imagined as bearing the weight of their own role.